 root of the project

We were not adding the CLI back then, most likely because it was a standard edition release.

Any particular reason to use v 4.5.9?

comment.body:
Hi @ducu,
our latest docker image contains `axonserver-cli.jar`  

After you run your axonserver instances in docker, if you are running one with tag `-dev` you can `/bin/bash` into and use the cli

Let's assume we run a node 
```
❯ docker run --rm \                                                   
  --name axonserver-1 \                                                            
  -v $(pwd)/vol/data/:/axonserver/data:z \
  -v $(pwd)/vol/events:/axonserver/events:z \
  -p 8024:8024 \
  -p 8124:8124 \
  --hostname axonserver-1 \
axoniq/axonserver:2023.1.2-jdk-17-dev
```
If you perform an `ls` command, I expect you will get back this result
```
❯ docker exec -it axonserver-1 ls -al axonserver-cli.jar
-rw-r--r--. 1 root root 4200977 Sep  1 06:29 axonserver-cli.jar
```

We can then start a bash inside our docker and perform our commands from there
```
❯ docker exec -it axonserver-1 /bin/bash
```
or if you prefer run the `java -jar axonserver-cli.jar` command without entering the docker
```
❯ docker exec -it axonserver-1 java -jar axonserver-cli.jar .....
```

If you prefer running axonserver-cli.jar on your host computer, you can grab the last one from https://download.axoniq.io/axonserver/axonserver-cli.zip

steer people in the right direction for these types of messages, but
still give them the opportunity to take an entirely different messaging
approach through the generic MessageBus
